x.php/Alqalam/article/view/718), [9](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22059764/).\n\n*   **Protein Content:** It is rich in high-quality protein, typically ranging from **18% to 20%** (though some studies have shown variations based on the cut and age of the animal)[8](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395318694_Nutritional_Composition_and_Quality_of_Camelus_dromedarius_Meat_from_Butcheries_in_Nouakchott_Mauritania), [4](https://journal.utripoli.edu.ly/index.php/Alqalam/article/view/718), [9](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22059764/).\n*   **Fat Composition:** Camel meat is known for being lean, with a fat content that is often lower than that of beef or goat, typically ranging from **1.2% to 5.8%**[8](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395318694_Nutritional_Composition_and_Quality_of_Camelus_dromedarius_Meat_from_Butcheries_in_Nouakchott_Mauritania), [4](https://journal.utripoli.edu.ly/index.php/Alqalam/article/view/718), [10](https://jcsp.org.pk/issueDetail.aspx?aid=0dc75d86-cad7-4c7e-bf53-d4394df037a4), [11](https://repository.sustech.edu/handle/123456789/16342). It contains essential fatty acids, including polyunsaturated fatty acids like linoleic acid[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9374515/), [4](https://journal.utripoli.edu.ly/index.php/Alqalam/article/view/718), [7](https://a-z-animals.com/blog/camel-meat-a-guide-to-the-nutritional-benefits-of-camel-meat/).\n*   **Other Nutrients:** It is a good source of iron, zinc, magnesium, potassium, and various vitamins, and it is generally lower in cholesterol than many other red meats[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9374515/), [8](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395318694_Nutritional_Composition_and_Quality_of_Camelus_dromedarius_Meat_from_Butcheries_in_Nouakchott_Mauritania), [7](https://a-z-animals.com/blog/camel-meat-a-guide-to-the-nutritional-benefits-of-camel-meat/), [9](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22059764/).\n\n### Risks: Additives and Processing\nWhile the raw meat is safe, gluten can be introduced through processing or preparation[1](https://www.beyondceliac.org/gluten-free-diet/is-it-gluten-free/meat/), [2](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4wGwVm4LX6XYdCCAxc1hrVd8PYeGXT78mf1MX3OF39xMHMV54kvip-8KCl6JPiYj4S1k_iJlrwC2cftsAvpeWwZ_MznE7DbEuQRLn0BC6_-RiijagGKdwqwjTSR--xb66Vy-KBMos6biIW7vR-VpuZsWq), [5](https://www.coeliac.org.uk/app/uploads/gluten-free-checklist-may-2024-1-1.pdf). Always check labels and ask questions about the following:\n\n*   **Processed Meat Products:** If you are buying camel sausages, meatballs, meat pastes, or marinated cuts, be aware that these often contain fillers, binders, or flavorings that may include wheat, barley, or rye[2](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4wGwVm4LX6XYdCCAxc1hrVd8PYeGXT78mf1MX3OF39xMHMV54kvip-8KCl6JPiYj4S1k_iJlrwC2cftsAvpeWwZ_MznE7DbEuQRLn0BC6_-RiijagGKdwqwjTSR--xb66Vy-KBMos6biIW7vR-VpuZsWq), [12](https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/health/special-diets/foods-you-think-are-gluten-free-arent), [5](https://www.coeliac.org.uk/app/uploads/gluten-free-checklist-may-2024-1-1.pdf), [13](https://gluten.org/2021/03/23/43-foods-where-gluten-may-be-hidden/).\n*   **Marinades and Sauces:** Pre-marinated meats or those served with sauces often contain soy sauce (which typically contains wheat), thickeners, or other gluten-based ingredients[1](https://www.beyondceliac.org/gluten-free-diet/is-it-gluten-free/meat/), [12](https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/health/special-diets/foods-you-think-are-gluten-free-arent), [5](https://www.coeliac.org.uk/app/uploads/gluten-free-checklist-may-2024-1-1.pdf), [13](https://gluten.org/2021/03/23/43-foods-where-gluten-may-be-hidden/).\n*   **Cross-Contact:** If you are eating out or buying from a deli counter, there is a risk of cross-contact[1](https://www.beyondceliac.org/gluten-free-diet/is-it-gluten-free/meat/), [2](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4wGwVm4LX6